The first virtual operator will already arrive, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long in coming.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written in mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming charges will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), has already said that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is a place for this type of operators and that they can succeed.
For the rest, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they only need to have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low expenses - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however, are often counteracted by the offer of more adjusted services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, the bet on a non-trivial target group can also be a good blow.
This operator specifically targets man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking – he's the operator he likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as Poland could hook our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the service offer, it is relatively saturated"
No chances in Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Quite the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in it, to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then, maybe better times are flashing.
It seems that, due to unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator on the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market is referred to by other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
He adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon "
Vodafone directs its attention rather to compliance with the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it precisely as the greatest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible offices - with operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and with it, a decrease in profits.
So why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the ČTÚ websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail great requirements for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the utter disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (ÚOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure was concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential interested parties was rather not interesting enough for the classic operators, "added Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Affairs of the ÚOHS.
These statements come as no surprise to the operators' representatives.
For offices that are supposed to represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, but they must also see to it that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the lowering of prices are not in the interest of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking in this whole case lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a fluke offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding promotion of responsibility in their actions in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of many sticking points.
Obviously, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary the agreement with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for ÚOHS the fact that three mobile operators ascend strikingly in a similar way should represent a warning.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators there are many similar impediments.
Placing the responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications of which the ÚOHS washes its hands of this whole matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently tabled to extend the competence of the ČTÚ in the field of commercial tenders which was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS should know this perfectly well, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything goes well, when no one is watching
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator continues to operate unnoticeably and there are already a few in Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile telephony services, which, however, only a part are public.
Normally these are companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases like those cited were discovered, we could speak of a violation of the conditions of the contract that could result in the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová responded to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators did not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a not inconsiderable profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name so they can not have it absolutely as a normal customer of the operators. "
This is precisely what should seem to the ČTÚ at all strange.
In addition, a new question appears for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators squint in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want to, it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we will stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, practically in all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, one market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at the moment the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases did they defend the operators but their customers.
Either with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to emerge the first virtual operator and with it began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really arrives in these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators allows a virtual mobile operator to enter, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, My Home.
The new anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, another with choir and one instrumental.
The singing is done by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
All four versions can iHNed.cz heard on the server.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio has said before that it intentionally chose for solos singers with young representative voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with both of us and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance," he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home was first played in 1834 on the stage of the State Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 naturally became a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the rise of the independent Czech Republic.
