The Southeast wanted to be part of the U.S. in a referendum
The Sudetenland Germans requested in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter that is kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this desire some groups of Sudeten Germans presumably addressed the U.S. president in 1945.
It results from letters kept in a private archive and now kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the "Šumava land" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have correctly understood the situation and we really want your word that American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators," the letter wrote, signed with a "people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts."
In view of the fact that the union of Czechoslovakia with the German South-East presumably supposes - according to them the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, disregard, incomprehension, pressure and slavery, the authors beg in the letter to the American president to assume Šumava forever under a protectorate.
"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants it will hand us over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way contributes to the victory of the Allies," the letter wrote.
The reason why the authors are unable to sign is presumably the fear of reprisals from "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president presumably doubted this idea of the German world, it would be enough to organize a referendum in the U.S. lands on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the U.S. or live under its patronage.
Although the text of the letter, with the current knowledge we have of post-war history, may sound a bit childish, according to some specialists it aptly paints the expectations of the Germans of the southeast of that time.
Although the Czech Germans must have sensed minimally that it was going to be about their expulsion from the republic, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others believed they would stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed even by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budějovice, enrolled in the Baltic navy.
When at the end of the war the British captured him and placed him in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that when they came home, Czech would be good for them," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners who lived before the war in Czechoslovakia, according to him, expected that on the basis of the Benes Decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
