Turkey broadens diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers had a desire to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 steps inland Asia, lies one of the most interesting relics of disastrous imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least, this is what the guides say.
The building is set to pierce the end of the platforms and has in front two towers, one for each corner, resembling to all a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in their complex is a bit decadent.
But once the vault box office was overcome, there is no doubt what the greatness of the company was that this was the westernmost door.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation consortium.
Germany, a "latecomer" in the imperial game, had ambitions to dominate the Middle East via this cured railway to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and its irregular Arabs.
Because of the relative isolation of surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell under
British rule and when forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was bad for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources commented that it was sabotage.
Since then the station was decaying and remained on the margins of history.
But today, this railway, gateway to Anatolia and all eastern centers, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to expand its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish Government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I climbed on a bunk bed and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the AKP's leaders, an expert on foreign policy, Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a trip of shocks, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - new city, designed to govern a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
which has raised some suspicion in the West and, especially, in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure – built ad hoc – in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and "power pastry shops" where middle-class managers in business suits – men and women – meet first thing in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighborhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today it has to look at the same time to the East and the West.
It is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
It has to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "Turkey might be forced to choose?"
"Turkey," he replies, "does not want to affront that choice."
He then underlines a point that almost everyone with whom I have spoken up to that point had recited to me almost by heart: the relations that Turkey has not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit to Europe and the United States as well as to Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically assemble those railway lines that open the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Again to Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts return to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building, 100 years ago.
How much would they have been surprised to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East would largely be in Turkey's hands today?
And waiting for the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So, there is not much doubt about which continent this fascinating country should claim.
