In this chapter of Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' positions on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a longtime associate in California studies and director of studies at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs School Choice."
Effectively appealing to Hispanic voters is a tough business.
Barack Obama's education proposals are an example of that.
Mr. Obama's campaign notes that "African-Americans and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students," and this is a very true consideration.
To combat such differences in learning events, Obama's education plan specifically advocates, among other things, "transitional bilingual education" for English-language learners.
However, the open question for Mr. Obama is whether the commitment of bilingual education, which prefers classroom instruction in languages other than English, is effective in overturning the gap in the final results.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an officially recognized elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
In this school the vast majority of students are Hispanic and from families with low income:
more than a third of students, many of whom are newcomers, are learning the English language.
However, an incredible 100 percent of fourth-year students have been tested positively on the 2008 math test.
and nearly an equally staggering 93 percent have mastered the English language and arts test.
This incredible success has been achieved using a different ingredient than what Mr. Obama favored.
The Sixth Street school emphasizes review and practice, the constant evaluation of competencies and does not tolerate any attitude of excuses.
In addition, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, the main of Sixth Street, the school's focus for English instruction to students is on "total immersion."
Immersion in English means the almost exclusive use of language in the treatment of the contents of instruction.
Ms. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, "We have had extraordinary successes with students like the latter who have come from Mexico and who, if you walk into the classroom 12 months later you wouldn't be able to pick up what was."
"It works," he said, "we think it works."
Will Mr. Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for replication by other schools with large populations of Hispanic-English students?
The results achieved by this school should remove any doubt about the answer, but the idea of his party's politicians on the issue of education (the Associations for National Education have long been advocates of bilingual education) and his very constant support for bilingual education obscure the prediction of Mr. Obama's response.
While it is that immigrants must learn English, recently Mr. Obama has trivialized the issue by letting people stop worrying about legislation that is only written in English.
And instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to improve the system and close loopholes, he should carefully consider models of education that work well, rather than disparage or trivialize them.
