Hidden by the expansion of the park to the theme of the big Orlando, a few miles from the bright, noisy and colossal city, is a quiet town, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first fully black town incorporated into the country and the childhood site of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 colored men, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools, and not a jail."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to pay tribute to Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described — making it also a tourist stop through its inclusion in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers' Project of Depression Season — remains a place apart.
The city remains independent, dignified and private as it was in the '30s, when Mrs. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida are often reluctant to share their true ideas with the white man, who "knows so little about us and who doesn't know what is being lost."
Even now, in the year in which a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has drawn attention to start a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain wary of the outsider.
"We're very cautious about the way our story is told," said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city's oldest church.
"It has to be correct."
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
