But, he adds, swinging in his chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was probably baptized, "she never stayed too long."
When Mrs. Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten about her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the '20s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
In Eatonville, there were no grand memorial ceremonies, no grand public readings.
