The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation from the community.
In the '50s, the struggle for racial mixing brought hatred closer to the community.
"During that season, a bunch of white guys would go around town throwing oranges and everything at the people sitting next to them," Mr. Franklin said.
