The victory over the road project has helped to change the image of the city itself.
Out-of-town people like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started coming to the church here in 1993, began to show up in large numbers, and residents began to revisit the past.
Eatonville entered the National Historic Register in 1998.
A new library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006, on a resurfaced and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly in Florida: Just six miles from downtown Orlando, you can, at times, feel like you're on a street of the past in a summer rain, in a town as small as the one that was founded by just 27 black families in the 1880s.
