Professor John Beckett writes:
in his Séquela de William Woodruff (September 25) you state that "in 1946 he resumed studies in economic history at Oxford and in 1950 he won a Houblon-Norman research fellowship... At the same time I was studying for a bachelor's degree, a master's degree and a doctorate degree."
This is learned in a note from Woodruff's author in Beyond Nab End, but it's not entirely correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, during which time he completed a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry, supervised by Professor J.D. Chambers, and subsequently published in 1958 under the title The British Rubber Industry.
