"I capture the master off stage to extract his character" Günther Bauer_Fotógrafo
No heels or ruffles or premiere costumes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of concentration on interpretation to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
To one side the artist.
To the other, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in those moments alien to the public, when finding the privacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of hands, carefree because they are not going to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser-known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different areas.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco-people" "can be ordinary people but, when seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "on the street" are artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy on stage... captivating the public.
To capture the personality of these artists you do not have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco".
With the flavor of the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1.997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, recall classic photography.
The application of different stylistic media breaks with the classical basis of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the action of the dance, the singing or the touch itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, which captivates the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the elf that becomes visible in a way of feeling, being and being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Fotómata.
Well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, make up this selection of almost seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of Veteran Athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love portraying people, getting to know them and being able to enter their life for a moment, whether it is a long or short moment.
I think that within photography portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You meet or confront people, characters, that sometimes you do not know, or that leave you only a few minutes to take the picture.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of current flamenco entitled "Flamenco-people" is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 Calle de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hércules, where it can be visited until October 16.
