The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, in particular, bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have developed this tiny robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to strengthen the collision avoidance capability of the brand's vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bee, capable of seeing with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately results in collision avoidance.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right angles or greater to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and principal engineer on this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected up or down, or diagonally; It can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allow it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn't require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This is the first step in developing new instantaneous collision avoidance technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium-ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles along the way.
