Talking in your sleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very clever telling us something that has happened the day before, but to children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens maybe you get a scare, but in reality it does not matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquios.
It is quite frequent, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (peeing asleep) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress situations or overexcitement.
Anyway it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also highly variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, single words, a murmur or the opposite (shouts, crying, long speeches ...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him an outlet in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will favor that the child can have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the somniloquias appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Do not wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed for several episodes it would be advisable to consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most usual), do not fall into the temptation of questioning him to extract information.
You will not achieve anything, because when he is asleep he is not conscious enough to organize his thought.
In addition you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
