The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary of its founding yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective suppliers of blood in the world.
And above all, it regained the trust of the public that had been seriously wavered by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and the discontent of the public, the government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and make recommendations so that such a disaster does not recur again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work during the years that followed, we have regained the public's trust," he says, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population henceforth had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " trust is extremely fragile. "
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, in Europe, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
So we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious disease can emanate from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we establish exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, some years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that make it possible to detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
The nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the moment in which the person has been infected and the moment in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today it is possible to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worry," says the head of the Héma-Québec directorate.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary pursues, before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"Needs increase because the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has an impact on the network of blood donors, which brings together on average only 3% of Québecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people in good health, aged 18 and meeting the eligibility criteria, can nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardships are very rare.
But the members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since life today is so rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate her blood," grieves Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart leaflets, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing in the bank of our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, "says Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this ", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
