As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party ends, Jean Charest was yesterday in Jean-Talon, in Quebec, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (of the left), tries to get elected during today's by-election.
Reject the limits of our last great northern frontier": such is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force staying in the broad lines, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis, yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, images were projected.
Paraded, on three huge screens, spectacular images of hydroelectric reservoirs, mining, Quebec as seen by "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Large media such as during the election period.
The prime minister thinks the election will take place this autumn, although he noted that his schedule was very full.
The " North Plane " is the fourth side of a "vision" the prime minister intends to have for Quebec, that of a " new economic space ", which includes a manpower agreement with France, an alliance between Canada and Europe, and harmonies with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the Prime Minister's speeches recently, the opening of the North – the northern territory to the 49th parallel – had never been the subject of a presentation.
The prime minister limited himself to explaining why the North was " a jewel to immense potential ", but did not give a term, investment amounts, or precise priority in future projects.
What could above all be more developed are: particularly hydroelectricity, the forest, but above all the mining sector, doped by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructures.
The North contains " nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and also diamond ", according to Mr. Charest's enumeration.
This " territory twice as big as France ", " is our home, it is in Quebec.
Not only is it our home, but it is in us," he insisted, as if to show that he was calling for a national founding myth.
Quebec built a lot thanks to its relationship with the North, he stressed: the flood towards gold in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
" It belongs to us, it's our future, " he added, having taken a theatrical pause to gaze at the immense map behind him.
The North, 70% of Québec territory, comprises a part of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, the prime minister said during the press conference.
"It's a traditional position that all governments reiterated.
There is a border line on which they have not agreed for a long time and, when the occasion arises, I reiterate that position on behalf of the government, "he said.
In addition, " with climate changes, we have to rethink our vision of the North, " he said speaking of the Northwest Passage, which will open every year due to the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the prime minister considers that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the inhabitants of the territory, the First Nations and the Inuites?
The prime minister said the Quebec government would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, particularly young people.
Two former ministers who come from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former deputy of the Quebec party of Ungava), have already begun consultations about thirty communities.
An inter-ministerial committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important role began some work.
The prime minister does not exclude an important meeting, " not necessarily a summit ", but a meeting in which " a common vision will be given ".
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The North Plan "will be concerted, orderly and respectful of the environment," he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as one that is in continuity with that of the liberal prime ministers who preceded him.
" Like the liberals who preceded us, we have thought differently to transform challenges into new opportunities for growth and development. "
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a big cocktail to underline the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's rise to power in the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois Power Station into Adélard-Godbout Reservoir.
" From Godbout, who created HydroQuebec, in Lesage who made the Revolution quiet and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, in Bourassa who made James Bay our party knew how to forge the future ", declared Juan Charest.
At the press conference, he invoked another reference, that conservative one, the "Roads to the North" program of John Diefenbaker, prime minister from 1957 to 1963.
Turning to the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric reservoir project, Mr. Charest stressed that its commissioning is planned for 2012.
"This stays with us, but I plan to be there," he confided to his militants, drawing applause.
Indeed, the prime minister, who said in April that no elections would take place in 2008 and certainly not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of launching a vote this autumn, which the law allows.
He stresses that his schedule is nevertheless full, particularly because of a mission of the federation council in China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend general council provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, particularly " constitutional aspirations " that had no trouble being accepted: the Liberal Party of Quebec demanded in particular recognition of the " specificity of Quebec " in the Constitution.
It also hoped that Quebec would appoint members of the Canadian Broadcasting and Telecommunications Council and that they would have a veto over decisions taken in Quebec.
On the side of the opposition, we welcomed the broad outlines of the Northern Plan with scepticism.
The head of the Parti Québécois, Pauline Marois, highlighted the Northern Québec Development Policy that the Landry government had launched in 2001.
According to her, the liberal government, coming to power in 2003, renounced applying it.
If he had, "we would make progress today," said Ms Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (vote that took place today), Françoise Mercure.
Quebec Democratic Action appeared to support the government's adoption of a Northern Plan.
"But what you want is that this is not fair a show," said leader Sebastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who returns from vacation today.
