Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world attempted a six-million-euro defamation suit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a " transparent public debate ".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to theirs?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the editor of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will muzzle the opposition as well as frighten whoever will dare to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is in front of the public that it would have had to present its vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by blows of a stick.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and rejects petitions and supporting letters for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate by disregarding his views?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word designates only highly paid lawyers and not for all Canadians; That represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand – or doesn't want to understand – is that the public that supports Noir Canada's authors and publishers does so mostly because it rejects the mining company's brutal way.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a gag persecution (pursuing the " public debate ", Barrick Gold has just deposited a request regarding the authors of Noir Canada urging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university pursuit and truth, essential for all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and debate the facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of many persecutions, who will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold truly wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The academic world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
The excessive persecution of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it intends, it does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the academic world, but also for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 30s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan aimed at curbing the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular: better control by those elected of its implementation, of new mechanisms aimed at ensuring the reimbursement of the public money invested, of the new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the leaders of the companies helped.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a marathon of negotiations that lasted two days.
"We made great progress toward a deal that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
"Everything has been done to cover the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the bottom line: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last hours because they feared the effect that a new failure would cause in the mood of investors.
The last time they had set was the opening of the markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have joined the negotiations late, were rather favorable to the agreement, without forgetting however to express their discontent of being forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow owners to keep their domicile and the salary of the leaders of the companies survived by the State.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked on another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: " I'd like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it. "
"The important points I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said that the option of doing nothing is not acceptable."
The $700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsellable assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans before spreading to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a freeze in liquidity and a disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It is a group of elected Republicans who had changed the first draft agreement, last week.
We believe we have broken the deadlock since Democrats agreed that certain "toxic" assets of distressed companies are only insured by the government, rather than bought.
To smooth out the rough edges for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision stipulating that if the government had to take losses for five years under this program, it could impose new rates that would be intended to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which 100 another billion can be added if the president deems necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will get stakes in the relief companies that will earn dividends in case of profits and that it will be able to sell again when the storm is over.
The federal government will have the possibility to delay foreclosure proceedings concerning homes obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and cash compensation paid to the leaders of companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see it voted on by the House of Representatives from today and the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all his efforts, he's still not sure his plan will pass.
Some people continued to protest this bill yesterday, both from Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents that " with all evidence, Washington does not want to understand. "
"We have a very serious financial problem.
There are solutions.
But not the taxpayer profit."
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, who is an animator for a small group in Congress, presents the problems differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to tell us: we ask Congress not to rush and to examine carefully the path to be taken," he declared yesterday.
At this very moment, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros ($16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been necessary after French bank BNP Paribas said it had given up buying its bankrupt competitor since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) during the U.S. subprime housing crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not wasted money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
Instead, we regained voting rights in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and families will appreciate now that times are uncertain. "
During this time, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to want to nationalize another bank suffering from the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley bank and more than 41 billion euros ($75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it is the one that would buy the branches and bank accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley Bank would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government would have to nationalize from the beginning of this financial crisis.
