What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on October 8, the criminal process will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, business, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used for their own purposes the funds obtained in public tenders, justifying on many occasions the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
Public funds and that of the municipalities - in their entirety about HUF 65 million - stopped partly in the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organization and partly in the pockets of individuals.
The method, which was also made known by the investigators, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in the public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were fake.
For this they obtained the checkbooks in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular stamps were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that in the name of which company the falsified invoice should be made was decided among others in that tour of the Superior Region of the Balaton where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model to make the invoices that they presented among others in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labor Affairs, as well as in the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the necessary reports to obtain public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
Well, a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however the bill consisted of one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of high-fantasy invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. because in the bookkeeping of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of that company, informed hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecution and shown the invoices, he already knew that they were false documents.
"On the stamp the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems he did not agree that according to the bill one hundred people stayed, since they have only eleven rooms in which there are not so many people.
In addition, meals were also included in the bill, while the restaurant has not worked for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest exclusively organises trips abroad, so that in the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated as a service a journey within Hungary, which was also not consistent with the agency's invoice issuing practice.
In addition, as it became known during the investigation, they included VAT in the document as well, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union was exempt from taxes.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with 25 but only 15 percent VAT, in addition the hotel employees only issued typed invoices however the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "shippers" also made other mistakes, as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as an activity carried out road transport to which - it was learned during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - the company founded as an investment consultant does not perform.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate format of the invoice, false stamp - it was learned that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI, are false. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also did not pay attention to the fact that when the Fiatal Városért Egyesület group ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, which is why the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They knowingly issued the invoices
Another group of manufacturers of false invoices are those who were aware that they had to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about four million HUF in the name of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. - according to the indictment - was convinced by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
Similarly, Biogate Kft., currently in liquidation, collaborated with Zuschlag and his accomplices, which in 2003 provided invoices worth approximately five million HUF to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, with no real economic activity behind it.
There was no movement of capital either, because later they canceled the prepared invoices but forgot to record this entity in their documents.
The next group of manufacturers of false invoices includes those who have some connection with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the plaintiff of the Ukrainian manager of the delta Trio SL with fictitious headquarters in Budapest, which dealt with the trade of fuels and vehicles.
This company issued numerous invoices worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer media.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which since September 14, 2005 has been under liquidation.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also dispatched the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices on behalf of the company for Atlasz, for Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually functioned due - according to the defendant - to the fact that they did not receive work.
But he took advantage of these companies, since at the request of his accomplice the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the registration documents of the company, they issued invoices in the name of the companies for the organizations linked to Zuschlag: for the Atlasz and for the Y-Generáció.
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade gave a total of 15 invoices to various entities worth HUF 14.2 million.
The Prosecutor's Office considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the amount of the invoices.
That man even took advantage of the limited partnership Szi-Beri to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont contest.
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a competition to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
From the contest they obtained 500 thousand HUF respectively, but did not use the money for the objectives of the contest.
Lest this be discovered, they submitted to the TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the search of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably recount in the trial - as they did in the Prosecutor's Office - the course of the falsification of the invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of the main defendant János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
For his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, this he has not done so to the present.
The question is: what is the interest of doing so?, because perhaps in exchange for the return of most of the money - fifty million HUF - the Socialists reached an agreement with him so that Zusi assumes all responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days could even be offended, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but it was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of economic crimes of far greater value, who never returned the money, walk freely or at least can wait in their own home for sentencing, he has no chance for that.
Psychology of overlays: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the groups of volunteers played lottery, the other participated in an auction and meanwhile the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games the participants could win money, but during the auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, when losing the game the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex intensified.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the real value of the product in question, and its members gambled.
Another group was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more in prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly 15 dollars before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, testing the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winning" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at New York University's economics school.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; Liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Pathogen-dependent hepatitis viruses are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humor (sperm, vaginal humor, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves by vaccine against virus A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and in the whites of the eyes jaundice, the stool becomes clear, the urine dark color and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year one million people die worldwide from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of those infected do not know they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore premature recognition, systematic medical control is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease can be cured if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so contagion can be suppressed and cancer prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
