Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in what way influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
As part of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while they were all looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of investigations in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside the academics.
The analysis occurred as follows; They attached a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the experiment participants to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, Sassoferrato's 17th century work and Leonardo da Vinci's Lady with the Ermine from the 15th century.
The researchers had hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the religious subject painting or the other.
Catholics said that by looking at the Virgin Mary they felt "safe" as "protected" people, "they were calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts."
Looking at the religious-themed painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so shocking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, such as for a mother or a father" - said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results, only one question remains: what effect would it have on pain regulation if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his stature?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On his tenth birthday Google can say: he can be found both in people's pockets and in the sky above his head; He knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to gather as much personal data about its users as possible, and this is necessary in order to meet the original goals of Google's founders: "Let's gather all the information in the world in one system!"
According to the leader of Google, the company even after ten years of work that stirred the world is still in the initial phase of the effort to be able to treat all the information.
To the question of what will happen in five years' time, Schmidt replied like this: he would like Google to be able to answer questions such as "What to do tomorrow?" or "What would be the job that would be best for me?" - however, software will not be able to answer seemingly simple questions until there is enough user information.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their browsing on the Internet, the searched keywords, IP addresses and the pages where they passed at the end of the search are stored precisely.
Thanks for example to Personalized Search that debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can return to consult what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches – in this same logic will be based the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they use my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who care watching Google's information monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a fact already confirmed that not only do they keep, but in justifiable cases they also transfer to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example of recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google gave the Brazilian government the information on its Web page, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
On the other hand, netizens who care about people's rights, in the month of May were relieved when the company together with the EFF, organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully proved in court that it was right in its litigation with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced.  through none of the points of the constitution to provide any type of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get about fifty thousand Web addresses and about a thousand phrases searched under the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of Web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is how the opinion about Google is quite contradictory: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is harmed by starting to use Google services, and rebel against it as against multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, Internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "vanguard corporation", not its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as conqueror of the World, no matter how much both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, or money for its applications, the code is open and the program package is constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between people's rights and the Internet that was produced precisely by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional footprints behind us and leveraging available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: to show ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even join them with other services, such as Twitter or the last.fm that offers a list of their music habits, then these can be included in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also have a blog,  where the latest photo galleries are automatically displayed and stored on Flickr or Picasa.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the girlfriend, seeing the flow of photographs the next morning of common friends, finds out with whom her fraudulent boyfriend spent the night before or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the direction of the company:  One thing is for sure, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
A person's "online" life is what he shows of himself - this is the definition behind the behavior of today's youth.
And those who want to hide something, or at least want to dodge Google's monopoly, can do so (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google's search system, but leaves no traces).
There are many people who do not want to register on the collective pages to avoid being found, but Google's online applications can be replaced, from text writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions which do not connect to gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion almost openly expects the day when Google shows its true face.
With its current value of $156 billion worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten ad agency revenues, while services that are being introduced more and more quickly cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft,  but also to numerous other software development companies.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example, senior management flatly rejected the employee protest after doubling the price of the company's daycare, considered the unlimited number of employee meals too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to pressure from the Chinese government and the company. The deal leaked any information that violated the good morals and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal regulations says that they will not announce any new services in advance, but only when it is ready to go, what is certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to stir the World: while some believe that Google's project of scanning and archiving books and magazines will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be summoned by the Court. Supreme of the United States, others fear their Health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analyzes, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database can provide good raw material for writers of science fiction works, the Scroogled, novel by the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwellian form that future, in which a man only from Google data can be described alarmingly well.
