The intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method to develop technologies to avoid collisions, if not imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example that of bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C robotic steering system imitating nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
An important role is played by the compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid the collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the vehicle's robot would not be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used rotary movement and acceleration as well as braking as a possibility for the robot of the car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, much less the storage.
This device in every second only has to process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte or megabyte memories are needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, within ten years can be incorporated into mass-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the existing obstacles in his way.
