The written version of the law of the financial rescue package of 700 billion dollars has been prepared that will be applied in several phases in order to buy the bad loans of the banks.
In the first phase half of the money will be spent.
According to Eastern Coast time during new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the financial rescue package of 700 billion dollars in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
We have made significant progress - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic speaker of the US Congress, affirming that it remains only to formalize the agreement in a document.
The compromise made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the commitment said: "This programme will work and be efficient but further action is needed. According to Pelosi, it's not about saving Wall Street, it's about turning the economic bandwagon around.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, that is, on Sunday before 8 pm, according to Washington time (that is, before two in the morning on Monday, according to Central European time), without causing a spectacular jump in the stock markets.
On the bill called the emergency law for economic stabilization of 2008, on Monday the US Congress will vote first and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy shoddy credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of which the Finance Ministry will buy poorly rated credit fund securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the chairman of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion may be spent after a new congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and credit fund securities, in addition to other "poisonous" type credits as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - informed competent people of the ministry.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the elements of concern, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: The law ensures in such a way the necessary financial means, that it can even reach 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it," he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and waiting for help from the state will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which American jargon simply calls a golden parachute.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of assistance from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys at auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes unless the bank's failed head retires.
By buying bad loans outright, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that bosses' severance payments are not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations refer only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the program.
This is the first case in U.S. history that a legal limitation on CEO income will be in place, said Barney Frank, a Democrat who chairs the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since ultimately they will even be able to make a profit with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
Under the bill, over the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return financial sector losses to taxpayers.
Of course on both sides there were those who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what the American citizens entrusted to us, that is, taxpayer dollars are not being protected," said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur said: The measures were urged by the very people who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared with last month's prices and by 12.9 per cent compared with August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1% from July 2008 and decreased by 3.9% from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices increased by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from a year earlier.
Industrial selling prices increased only minimally at 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8%), mainly due to a 4.6% monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5% increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials industry (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimal extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry, prices increased by between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight in domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was registered in August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year, the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded by 18.7 percent the prices of the previous year.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the prices of the energy sector and intermediate sectors there were no changes from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month last year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods producing industries, there was a decrease of 6.8 per cent and in investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month fell by 1.7 per cent against the euro and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
