Fox in the chicken coop
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when viewing drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programs for the protection of personal data, which binds the use of prescription data in all cases to the approval of the given person.
It must be in independent hands, because if not, "we entrust the chicken coop to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the health status of the client and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the client to medical control and signed the contract with him already knowing the result of the control.
Dick ten years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: with the customer identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the client.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, you indicate that the level of fat in your blood is practically incurably high, so you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company in addition to the administration hardly has anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is for example that some medications are multipurpose, for example certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk increase factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities already force them to do this, although they did not receive a fine for the negligence of until now.
Some companies lately also elaborate the results of laboratory tests and combining them with drug consumption data obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those that provide health services.
The bill that gives the right to the authority for the control of specialized companies for the provision of personal data is already before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the individual for the provision of their own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, despite everything, are exposed to the goodwill of the fox.
