Yesterday's New York Times confirms that the ongoing crisis is disarming the Republican Party, always more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance.  strong especially in the Central and Southern states.
The soul, in fact, that has become arrogant with the vote of the one who spoke at the beginning.
This barely cited is just one example of the mutations, of the great mutations, that the ongoing economic earthquake heralds: not only in the United States but in the entire West and not only here only.
Both in the United States and in Europe for some time the crisis seems to work as an accelerator of incubation phenomena that with the new climate solidify and come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary reactivation, of the double state-sovereignty category in relation to a type of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in effect, is a crisis of banking institutions - which have, yes, strong financial relations with the outside, but above all the balance sheets of families living in a single country and in a single state are much more compromised.
The one that immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulty and protests of those people and those families who, on the other hand, are voters.
The crisis appears economically global but it is politically and exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems substantially out of the game or they don't have much to say: the crucial test is the European Union, which divided as always between different interests and different state strategies fails to decide on any common policy.
It is from the government of each state that everyone expects an intervention, rescue and reactivation plans, new rules and above all the subsidy of funds: from the moment the cut is reached it is only the state that has the economic resources and the mass of financial resources to remedy things.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of incalculable value, values in certain circumstances in which no market and no organization can ever dispose of to the same extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the nation-state is perfectly in tune, with the greatest importance whenever the new development of the economy tends to attribute it to a factor closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had entered the network of ever more sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to dominate the world, we realized that our future will instead have to do the math more and more with the little immaterial things like water,  crops and oil.
All things that, mind you, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are equally united in an absolute way in a circumscribed space, a territory.
So whoever is as sovereign certainly has many more cards than he who is not, and who has the misfortune of living in a position without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty that but presages a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics and Leadership.
In this sense, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the objective awareness of the need for leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take the situation into hand.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, of inadequate economic species relieved with many dark areas.
And together something deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, a intolerance, an inadequate image, a sense of remoteness, which tends to involve the entire ruling class of the countries of the West in increasing numbers.
It seems to advance more and more, in various places of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same as those of the social elites so far booming, the same way of feeling and being, their culture in the comprehensive exception of the term, to have made their own time and to be more foreign to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership, in short, feeds underground a branching but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifest themselves in an electoral "revolt" or in the sudden changes of collective moods of recent times, from the conservative exit in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of the social-democratic consensus in Britain.  to the rebellion of the men of the American Congress against Bush (and layers also with the victory of the right in Italy that has something to do with it).
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format I would say some, make it increasingly difficult to understand and then to represent, what from today that is taking shape are the deep strata of Western society and that the economic crisis renews.  It increases and potentially agitates excessively.
In the face of all this, to speak of a "mass rebellion" today is frankly exaggerated.
But having your eyes open certainly isn't.
The super glue for walking on walls
Overcome the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and in the future walk on walls like spider-man.
It is the goal of several American research centers and now a team of four institutes has come quite close.
With an adhesive of only 2.5 square centimeters, scientists have been able to glue a body of 100 kilos on a vertical wall.
THE STUDY – The American journal Science has published the findings of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the team of researchers is an evolution of existing ones that use a particular carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have been inspired by the legs of geckos, coated with microscopic hairs that can ensure the animal a perfect adhesion.
Tests done on different materials, such as glass, Teflon and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful from the legs of this reptile and at the same time "detaches easily from the walls," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the School of Engineering at the University of Dayton.
WALK ALONG THE WALLS? "This material could be useful as a transient adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Layers to walk on the walls exactly like spider-man? Layers do, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use as the connection between electronic devices, because carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications could have to do with aerospace engineering.
At the moment no superheroes.
OTHER RESEARCH - The University of California, Berkeley, is also looking for a new adhesive.
In an article in the journal American Chemical Society, Californian scholars have presented an adhesive made of microfibers such as hairs that self-clean from dust during movement on a surface to always maintain perfect adhesion.
