The Economics Novel to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize in Economics has been awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his studies, his trade models and on the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is a noted New York Times editorialist.
Krugman is one of the Bush administration's biggest critics of economic and foreign policy decisions.
A few months after the attack of September 11, 2001, in those days that bankrupted Enron, Krugman had foreseen in an editorial published by the New York Times that the second event would be more decisive than the first, in terms of consequence for the United States.
A forecast that triggered much controversy and that for several years was reproached to the economy, but now it has been revealed to be accurate.
"I'm surprised and a little upset that the memory of the Enron and Worldcom collapse scandal has quickly disappeared from the public eye," Krugman told the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the executive committee of the European central bank, Krugman is an "economist of great value", but also a popularizer with a "very aggressive" style, particularly critical of the excesses of liberalism of the Bush administration.
Open Office, echo the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
It is the day of the launch of OpenOffice.org 3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to attract more and more users, from the home to the office to public administration professionals, as a free alternative to the well-known Microsoft Office.
After a work of almost a year on the part of the volunteer developers, of which their backs are monitored by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office is shown to the public with several new features: to the welcome screen and the less rude magazine interface, more consistent ones are added, such as compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, the latest ISO standard version.
Attention also paid to multi-functioning with the Office 2007 suite, Open Office is able to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting some specific functions of some modules such as the one that allows you to reduce the dimension of the PowerPoint presentation, useful for example, to send it via electronic post, or the possibility of importing the PDF file into the graphic elaboration module, preserving the original appearance of the page.
Always on this front you can create "hybrid PDF" documents, which accumulate the typical graphic of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or a text processor.
The Collaboration is an element that has received different improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet they can intervene in different users, avoiding the conflicts of the modificas, in the elaboration of texts, each collaborator is given a color in the comment for a better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are also working to bring some OpenOffice features to the Web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they should give the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at the http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html address and added to the English version that was in the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual the suite is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request the installation CD can also be sent home or to work.
And if the theme of the free can be a hook for dissemination in the houses, it is in business field that Open Office the suite tests, tries the big bet, being able to already have several projects carried out in the public administration and in schools.
And there is not even a lack of realities that offer an ideal training, consultation and assistance service for small and medium-sized enterprises, in which business prospects could be opened.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for video writing the corresponding Word; Calc, is the spreadsheet that replaces Excel; Impress, for Powerpoint presentation; Dbase, as in the case of the well-known Access is the program that consents to work on the data base; and finally Draw the graphic module.
Goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million download, and considering that until today we have reached almost 3 million 600 thousand, with the release of the new version it is likely that the expected figure can be exceeded.
