Steve Fossett's plane found the millionaire disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris has been found on a plateau at 3000 meters altitude, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
The commissioner of Madera County, John Anderson, has dispelled the doubts that still remained: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is typical of what Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance "he said in a stamp conference.
The commissioner has specified that no human remains have been found either on the plane or in the surroundings.
The millionaire, 63, has been presumed dead in February.
The American office for transportation safety (NTSB) has made it known that a few hours after the sighting of the wreckage, a squad of investigators has been sent to identify the device: it is typical of the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the border of Nevada, some of Fossett's personal remains have been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents with Fossett's name on them, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
The search for Fossett had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the turn of the world in a hot air balloon: two solitary weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the tour of the world by plane and non-stop.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
