Students victims of expensive rent, up to 900 euros for a room
The rental market for university students does not know the crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room could cost a student 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has already assumed very serious characteristics to the point of excluding the right to study to a large part of young people because of the very high costs that the family would have to sustain – explains the head of the Sunia studies office, Laura Mariani – in these cities the strong demand has totally deformed the market to the point of triggering a process of generalized increase even for residents. "
Apart from the fact that in most cases rental offers contain a series of violations: free type contracts, not registered, without canon limit, linked sub-rentals.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions are needed that, through the revision of tax taxation, prices can be regulated.
Looking in detail at the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in Brianza area, they serve approximately 450 euros; for a single room from a minimum of 650 (Bande Nere area) to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 (in Victoria area).
In Florence a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room approximately 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the areas near the University, they serve 250/280 euros for a bed in a double room and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome in the central areas near the University (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) they ask you approximately 600 euros for a single room and 450 for a bed in a double room.
Only slightly lower values (550 euros for a single room) in areas near other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
Savings are made only if you change peripheral area: 300 euros for a bed and 450 for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and surroundings.
In Naples for a bed they serve you 300/450 euros, for a room you spend from 400 to 600 euros, with the highest prices in the Polyclinic, Vomero and Colli Aminei areas.
In Bari for a bed they serve you 250/350 euro, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities prices are lower in absolute terms, but it has a greater weight in the economy of the city.
In cities such as Perugia, where the phenomenon of rents to students and non-EU students is more frequent, there is a further anomaly: an increase of 25/30% in the fee for foreign students compared to Italians.
Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic cinemas
Historic cinemas close favoring Multiplexes.
"A city without movie theaters in a blind city, it's like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the great Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono cinemas in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom a piece of place and so much emotion was shared", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize at Cannes,  that told the poetry of a provincial movie theater and nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that lost perhaps forever.
The figures given by Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and most of them are paid for by the main cinemas in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, it is typical of these three Italian regions that have registered the largest number of new meticon cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of existing ones, because when a city hall closes, not all its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of merchants: the previous state debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year. "
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that worried about closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the mono cinema either in the historic center or in the periphery.
Among the planned rules there are means of fiscal facilitation in favor of managers and advantages for the public in mobility terminations: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
"It's an initiative I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example by setting up other measures.
It is true that to contrast the extra power of the meticones, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that was always important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New cinema Paradiso", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the posters blackened by dust, I turn to the other side.
